##Executive Summary
Financial institutions process thousands of transactions every day, making it impossible for fraud analysts to manually review every transaction. Fraud detection systems therefore play an important role in prioritizing suspicious transactions for investigation while minimizing unnecessary reviews.

This project developed a machine learning solution for suspicious transaction triage using a binary classification approach. The objective was to predict whether a transaction should enter the fraud investigation queue based only on information available at the time of the transaction.

The project followed the complete machine learning lifecycle, including problem framing, exploratory data analysis, preprocessing, feature engineering, model training, evaluation, and deployment. Several classification algorithms were trained and compared, including a Dummy Classifier, Logistic Regression, Decision Tree, and Random Forest. The final model was selected based on evaluation metrics such as Precision, Recall, F1-score, and ROC-AUC.

A Streamlit application was developed to demonstrate the model and allow users to enter transaction details and receive an understandable prediction and recommendation. The model is intended as a decision-support tool and should complement, rather than replace, human fraud analysts.


1.Problem Framing

*Stakeholder*

The primary stakeholders are fraud analysts and the fraud risk management team responsible for reviewing potentially fraudulent financial transactions.

Operational Decision

The operational decision is whether a transaction should be added to the manual fraud investigation queue.

Unit of Analysis

Each row in the dataset represents one financial transaction.

Machine Learning Task

This project addresses a supervised binary classification problem.

Target Variable

The target variable is is_fraud, where:

0 = Legitimate Transaction
1 = Fraudulent Transaction
Prediction Horizon

The prediction is made immediately after a transaction is initiated using only information available at that moment.

Cost Analysis
False Positive

Legitimate transactions may be unnecessarily investigated, increasing operational costs and customer inconvenience.

False Negative

Fraudulent transactions may go undetected, resulting in financial losses and reputational damage.

Non-use

Without machine learning, analysts may overlook fraudulent transactions due to the large transaction volume.

Success Criteria

The project aims to achieve:

High Recall to detect fraudulent transactions
Good Precision to reduce unnecessary investigations
Strong F1-score
High ROC-AUC


2. Dataset Description

The project uses the Credit Card Fraud 10K dataset.

Features
>transaction_id
>amount
>transaction_hour
>merchant_category
>foreign_transaction
>location_mismatch
>device_trust_score
>velocity_last_24h
>cardholder_age
>is_fraud

The transaction_id column was removed before modelling because it is a unique identifier and does not contribute predictive information.

The target variable is is_fraud.

The dataset was stored in its original form within the data/raw directory, while cleaned and engineered datasets were stored separately in the data/processed directory.


3. Exploratory Data Analysis

Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA) was conducted before any preprocessing to understand the dataset and identify potential modelling challenges.

The following analyses were performed:

Dataset dimensions
Data types
Missing values
Duplicate records
Target class distribution
Numerical feature distributions
Correlation analysis
Outlier detection
Key Findings
Fraudulent transactions represented a smaller proportion of the dataset than legitimate transactions, indicating class imbalance.
Transaction amounts exhibited a right-skewed distribution with several high-value outliers.
Device trust scores varied considerably, suggesting they could provide useful predictive information.
Velocity of transactions during the previous 24 hours appeared to be associated with fraud risk.
Foreign transactions combined with location mismatch appeared more frequently among fraudulent cases.

These findings influenced preprocessing, feature engineering, and model selection.

(Insert EDA figures here.)


4. Data Preprocessing

The following preprocessing steps were performed:

Removed duplicate records
Handled missing values
Dropped the transaction identifier
Split data into training and testing sets
Applied StandardScaler to numerical features
Applied OneHotEncoder to categorical variables
Implemented preprocessing using a scikit-learn Pipeline and ColumnTransformer

To prevent data leakage, all preprocessing transformations were fitted only on the training data before being applied to the test data.


5. Feature Engineering

Several new features were created using only information available at prediction time.

These included:

Amount Category
Age Group
Transaction Period
High Velocity Indicator
Low Device Trust Indicator
Foreign Location Risk
Log-transformed Transaction Amount

These engineered features provide additional information that may improve fraud detection while maintaining operational realism.


6. Model Development and Comparison

A Dummy Classifier was first trained to establish a simple non-machine-learning baseline.

Three supervised machine learning algorithms were then evaluated:

Logistic Regression
Decision Tree
Random Forest

Hyperparameter tuning was performed using cross-validation to identify the best-performing model.

The evaluation focused on Precision, Recall, F1-score, and ROC-AUC because the cost of missing fraudulent transactions is significantly higher than investigating legitimate ones.

